# Agent Workflow

## Your Mindset
You are not a code generator. You are an engineer.
Think before you type. Plan before you code. Verify before you ship.
Every task must be understood, decomposed, implemented cleanly, and confirmed to work.

## Your Ruleset
The `(rule-name)` references throughout this workflow point to dedicated rules.
Load and apply them at the relevant step — they contain the full detail for that concern.
```
agent-workflow.mdc              ← you are here — follow this first
composability.mdc               ← how to structure code
unit-testing.mdc                ← how to test and hit 100% coverage
how-to-use-comments.mdc         ← when to comment and when not to
how-to-document.mdc             ← how to write markdown docs
break-down-implementation.mdc   ← how to plan and commit
validate-input-and-output.mdc   ← how to confirm data at runtime
error-handling.mdc              ← how to handle, wrap, and propagate errors
golang.mdc                      ← language-specific standards
```

Do not summarize or skip rules. Each one has a stopping condition — meet it before moving on.

## The Workflow — Follow In Order

### 1. Understand
- Read the task fully before doing anything.
- Read the relevant code — do not assume what it does, trace it.
- Identify the data flowing through the area you are changing. Confirm its shape at runtime. (`validate-input-and-output`)
- If anything is ambiguous, state your assumption explicitly before proceeding.

### 2. Plan
- Decompose the work into a logical commit sequence before writing any code. (`break-down-implementation`)
- Identify which files will change and why.
- Identify the test cases you will need before writing the implementation.
- State the plan as a short ordered list. Do not skip this step.

### 3. Implement
- Write code in small, composable units. (`composability`)
- Handle every error explicitly — wrap with context, propagate to the correct layer. (`error-handling`)
- No comments that restate what the code does. (`how-to-use-comments`)
- Follow language-specific standards throughout. (`golang`)
- Commit each logical unit before moving to the next. (`break-down-implementation`)

### 4. Test
- Write unit tests alongside each unit of implementation. (`unit-testing`)
- Run coverage. Iterate until 100%. Do not move on with gaps. (`unit-testing`)
- Use real fixture data — never invent it. (`validate-input-and-output`)
- Test every error path — not just the happy path. (`error-handling`)

### 5. Document
- Write or update the markdown doc for every package or file touched. (`how-to-document`)
- No placeholder text, no incomplete sections. (`how-to-document`)

### 6. Verify
- Re-read your own diff before considering the task done.
- Every exported symbol is tested and documented.
- Coverage is 100%.
- All commits are atomic with messages that describe the change without reading the diff.
- No debug code, commented-out code, or TODOs without a ticket.
- No swallowed errors, no bare returns, no panics in business logic. (`error-handling`)

## Rules That Always Apply
- Never assume data shape — confirm it at runtime. (`validate-input-and-output`)
- Never swallow, ignore, or panic on an error — handle or propagate it. (`error-handling`)
- Never leave a task half-done. If you are blocked, say so explicitly.
- Never make a large change in one commit. (`break-down-implementation`)
- Never skip tests because the logic seems simple. (`unit-testing`)

## Done Means
- [ ] Implementation is complete and composable.
- [ ] Every error is handled, wrapped with context, and tested.
- [ ] Tests pass with 100% coverage including error paths.
- [ ] Documentation is written and accurate.
- [ ] Commits are atomic with clean messages.
- [ ] Diff has been reviewed — no noise, no leftovers.